From: AliceVision-for-Mac port <alex@bsa.ai>
Subject: [PATCH] meshroom/__init__.py: add Darwin DYLD_FALLBACK_LIBRARY_PATH

On macOS the dynamic loader honours DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH /
DYLD_FALLBACK_LIBRARY_PATH, not LD_LIBRARY_PATH. The existing
else-branch silently failed on Darwin when the AliceVision binaries
were not built with an embedded @rpath. Add an explicit
`sys.platform == "darwin"` branch that sets DYLD_FALLBACK_LIBRARY_PATH
(preferred over DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH because it only kicks in when the
loader cannot find the dylib via the binary's own install-name / rpath,
so we do not override system frameworks).

Our mac AliceVision build does encode @rpath install names, so in the
common case this branch is a no-op safety net for users who unpack a
prebuilt bundle into a non-standard location.

--- a/meshroom/__init__.py
+++ b/meshroom/__init__.py
@@ -200,6 +200,13 @@
     addToEnvPath("PATH", os.environ.get("ALICEVISION_BIN_PATH", ""))
     if sys.platform == "win32":
         addToEnvPath("PATH", os.environ.get("ALICEVISION_LIBPATH", ""))
+    elif sys.platform == "darwin":
+        # macOS: dyld honours DYLD_FALLBACK_LIBRARY_PATH. Prefer fallback over
+        # DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH so we do not shadow system frameworks; this only
+        # kicks in when the binary's own @rpath / install-name cannot resolve
+        # the dylib. The mac AliceVision build embeds @rpath, so this is a
+        # safety net for relocated bundles.
+        addToEnvPath("DYLD_FALLBACK_LIBRARY_PATH", os.environ.get("ALICEVISION_LIBPATH", ""))
     else:
         addToEnvPath("LD_LIBRARY_PATH", os.environ.get("ALICEVISION_LIBPATH", ""))
 
